[1]
Date: Tue 2 Dec 2014
Source: GlobalMeatNews [edited]
http://www.globalmeatnews.com/Industry-Markets/Avian-influenza-found-in-wild-ducks-in-Netherlands


Two samples from wild ducks around the area of Kamerik, Woerden [Utrecht province], in the Netherlands, have tested positive for a highly pathogenic H5 strain of avian influenza, Rijksoverheid.nl [Dutch government's website] confirmed in a statement last night (1 Dec 2014) [see comment].

[Byline: Georgi Gyton]

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
Gut Laach
D-52385 Nideggen
Germany
http://www.cvlonghorns.de

[According to the official notification cited above, the sampling in Kamerik (Utrecht province, central Netherlands) is part of the investigation into the possible role of wild birds in the spread of bird flu in the Netherlands.

In addition: an analysis by the Central Veterinary Institute (CVI) led to the conclusion that the 3 HPAI H5N8 outbreaks in Hekendorp, Ter Aar, and Kamperveen occurred independently. This was informed to the parliament in a letter from Sharon Dijksma, State Secretary of Economic Affairs. Such a finding underlines the role of wild birds as a source of infection.

The letter from the State Secretary and the press release above are available (in Dutch) at http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/nieuws/2014/12/01/vogelgriep-aangetroffen-bij-wilde-eenden.html. The revised control measures, addressed in the letter, are presented in item [3] below. - Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Tue 2 Dec 2014
Source: Expatica/NL News [edited]
http://www.expatica.com/nl/news/country-news/Wild-ducks-are-carrying-bird-flu-say-researchers_441321.html


Excrement from 2 wigeons, a variety of wild duck, was tested for the virus at the Netherlands ecology institute and found to have the highly-infectious H5 variant of avian flu.

It is not yet known if it is the same N type as the virus found in the 5 outbreaks recorded in the Netherlands over the past 2 weeks, Trouw reports.

"We now know that these wigeons carry the avian flu virus, but there could also be other kinds of migratory birds which are infected," virologist Ron Fouchier told broadcaster Nos.

It is not clear how the virus was transferred to chickens kept in sheds but Fouchier says it is possible that wigeon droppings were carried from fields into the sheds on the shoes of farmers.

The most recent outbreak in the Netherlands was discovered on [Sun 30 Nov 2014] at a chicken farm in Zoeterwoude [South Holland province].

Researcher Henk van der Jeugd told Nos radio that the intensive poultry sector will remain vulnerable to bird flu.

"We need to think about how we will deal with it in the future because it will keep coming back," he said. Meanwhile, poultry sector organisation Nepluvi said on [Tue 2 Dec 2014] that now it appears wild duck are to blame for spreading the disease, the government needs to change its approach.

In particular, the rules on moving poultry and eggs should be relaxed in areas without large expanses of water where wild ducks congregate, the organisation said.

Sector representatives are due to discuss the economic impact of the recent bird flu outbreak with government officials later on [Tue 2 Dec 2014].

