******
[3]
Date: Tue 2 Dec 2014
Source: Press release, Dutch Ministry of Economic Affairs [in Dutch, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/ministeries/ez/nieuws/2014/12/02/betere-hygiene-en-maatwerk-bij-aanpak-vogelgriep.html


[Sharon] Dijksma, State Secretary for Economic Affairs, addressed today (2 Dec 2014) ) in a letter to the parliament, an adapted package of measures to combat avian influenza in the Netherlands. The new measures go into force Thu 4 Dec 2014 at 00:00 am.

Dijksma: "We are doing everything possible to combat the spread of bird flu in the Netherlands. In addition, I rely increasingly on the latest data and expert opinions. For the industry, this means that a number of drastic measures remain in force, but where possible these are customized."

Introduction of bird flu research
The recent discovery of the highly pathogenic avian flu virus in 2 wigeons is an indication that avian flu has entered the Netherlands by means of these wild ducks. Furthermore, experts conclude that in all regions there are sporadic infections with the virus.

Measures
The measures in the 10-km [6 mi] zone around the infected farms remain in force. Also in the west of the Netherlands (region A), where most infections have been found, all restrictive measures such as a total ban on movements of poultry, eggs, poultry manure, and used bedding are to be maintained. The prohibition of hunting is maintained as well.

Focus on hygiene
In other regions, repopulation of culled farms is permitted and the hunting ban lifted. The 'collecting ban' will be maintained [banning the transport of poultry to and the holding of concentrations of animals such as in markets, auctions, exhibitions, etc., [as well as visitors schemes.] Transporting vehicles will be allowed, during the coming period, to visit only one poultry farm/plant per voyage, followed by cleaning and disinfection of the vehicle. To prevent the introduction of avian influenza into poultry houses, drastic hygiene measures should be applied. To facilitate this, discussions about the arrangements will be held with the sector.

No bird flu virus has been detected on the farms within the 10-km [6 mi] zone around the infected holding in Zoeterwoude.

